{"title_page": "Quorum of the Twelve", "text_new": "{{short description|Governing body in Latter Day Saint religious movement}}\n{{For|the fictional political group in Battlestar Galactica|Colonial Day}}\n{{refimprove|date=February 2018}}<!--many paragraphs lacking citations, as well as entries in the table of members-->\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\nIn the [[Latter Day Saint movement]], the '''Quorum of the Twelve''' (also known as the '''Council of the Twelve''', the '''Quorum of the Twelve Apostles''', '''Council of the Twelve Apostles''', or the '''Twelve''') is one of the governing bodies or ([[Quorum (Latter Day Saints)|quorums]]) of the church hierarchy organized by the movement's founder [[Joseph Smith]], and patterned after the [[Apostles]] of [[Jesus]] (see [[Commissioning of the Twelve Apostles]]). Members are called [[Apostle (Latter Day Saints)|Apostles]], with a special calling to be [[evangelism|evangelistic]] ambassadors to the world.\n\nThe Twelve were designated to be a body of \"traveling councillors\" with jurisdiction outside areas where the church was formally organized (areas of the world outside of [[Zion (Latter Day Saints)|Zion]] or its outlying [[Stake (Latter Day Saints)|Stake]]s). The Twelve were designated as being equal in authority to the [[First Presidency]], the [[Seventy (Latter Day Saints)|Seventy]], the standing [[presiding high council]], and the [[High council (Latter Day Saints)|High Councils]] of the various [[Stake (Latter Day Saints)|stakes]].<ref>LDS Church [[Doctrine and Covenants]] 107:25\u201327, 36\u201337.</ref>\n\nAfter the [[death of Joseph Smith]] in 1844, permanent [[schism|schisms]] formed in the movement, resulting in the formation of various churches, many of which retained some version of the Quorum of the Twelve.\n\n==Members of the Quorum, prior to 1844==\nIn 1835, the [[Three Witnesses]] were asked by Smith to select the original twelve members of the church's Quorum of the Twelve. They announced their choices at a meeting on February 14, 1835.<ref name = hc>''[[History of the Church (Joseph Smith)|History of the Church]]'' [http://www.kristus.dk/jkk/text.php?id=90062 '''2''':186\u201387].</ref> The Three Witnesses also ordained the twelve chosen men to the priesthood office of apostle by the laying on of hands, with the ordinations taking place between February and April 1835.<ref name = hc/>\n\nBelow is a list of members of the Quorum prior to the [[Succession crisis (Latter Day Saints)|succession crisis of 1844]] (including those ordained after the original Twelve). A total of 18 different men were members of the Quorum during this period.\n\nIn 1838, four members of the Quorum were excommunicated and the President of the Quorum resigned.<ref>http://www.josephsmithpapers.org/person/thomas-baldwin-marsh,</ref> (President Marsh was-excommunicated in absentia in 1839). Of the five, two of them would later rejoin with [[Brigham Young]] and [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church) after the 1844 schism, but they would never resume their former places in the Quorum.  Two others would join various sects (with varying degrees as to the acceptance of their apostleship) and never returned to the LDS Church, while the fifth member left the Mormon movement completely.  A sixth member of the Quorum was killed in 1838.\n\nAfter the 1844 schism, ten of the then-Quorum members followed Young to the [[Salt Lake Valley]]. Two others left and joined other sects.\n\n{| border=\"1\" class=\"wikitable\"\n! width=\"55\" |\n! width=\"150\" | Name\n! width=\"150\" | Dates ordained\n! width=\"940\" | [[Succession crisis (Latter Day Saints)|Post-succession]] crisis affiliations\n|-\n|\n| [[Thomas B. Marsh]]\n| April 26, 1835 \n| Excommunicated from the [[Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)|Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints]]<ref name = \"Naming\">Joseph Smith's original organization was named ''Church of Christ''.  In 1834, the official name changed to \"Church of the Latter Day Saints\" and again, in 1838, to \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints\". See:<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ''Manuscript History of the Church'', LDS Church Archives, book A-1, p. 37; reproduced in Dean C. Jessee (comp.) (1989). ''The Papers of Joseph Smith: Autobiographical and Historical Writings'' (Salt Lake City, Utah: Deseret Book) '''1''':302\u2013303; H. Michael Marquardt and [[Wesley P. Walters]] (1994). ''Inventing Mormonism: Tradition and the Historical Record'' (Salt Lake City, Utah: Signature Books) p. 160.</ref> in 1839. [[President of the Quorum of the Twelve|President of the Quorum]] from 1835 to 1839. Later rejoined with Brigham Young and the LDS Church in 1857, but did not resume his former place in the Quorum.\n|-\n|\n| [[David W. Patten]]\n| February 15, 1835\n| Remained a member of the Quorum until he was killed in 1838.\n|-\n| <center>[[File:Brigham Young by Charles William Carter.jpg|50px]]</center>\n| [[Brigham Young]]\n| February 14, 1835\n| [[President of the Quorum of the Twelve|President of the Quorum]] beginning in 1839. Young became the [[List of presidents of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|2nd]] President of the LDS Church in 1847.\n|-\n| <center>[[File:Heber Chase Kimball-2.png|50px]]</center>\n| [[Heber C. Kimball]]\n| February 14, 1835\n| Remained with the LDS Church and Brigham Young after 1844. In 1847, Kimball became [[First Presidency (LDS Church)|First Counselor]] to Young.\n|-\n| <center>[[File:Orson Hyde.jpg|50px]]</center>\n| [[Orson Hyde]]\n| February 15, 1835\n| Remained with the LDS Church and Brigham Young after 1844. In 1847, Hyde became [[President of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles (LDS Church)|President]] of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles.\n|-\n| <center>[[File:Williamemlellin.gif|50px]]</center>\n| [[William E. McLellin]]\n| February 15, 1835 \n| Excommunicated from the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints<ref name = \"Naming\"/> in 1838. After 1844, McLellin joined for a short time multiple sects, including the [[Rigdonite]], [[Strangite]], [[Whitmerite]] and [[Hedrickite]] sects, each of which recognized his apostleship.\n|-\n| <center>[[File:Parley P Pratt.gif|50px]]</center>\n| [[Parley P. Pratt]]\n| February 21, 1835\n| Remained with the LDS Church and Brigham Young after 1844 and continued within the Quorum until he was [[Parley P. Pratt#Death and legacy|killed in 1857]].\n|-\n| <center>[[File:Lukesjohnson.gif|50px]]</center>\n| [[Luke S. Johnson]]\n| February 15, 1835\n| Excommunicated from the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints<ref name = \"Naming\"/> in 1838.  Later rejoined with Brigham Young and the LDS Church in 1846, but did not resume his former place in the Quorum.\n|-\n| <center>[[File:Williamsmith.gif|50px]]</center>\n| [[William Smith (Latter Day Saints)|William Smith]]\n| February 15, 1835\n| On May 24, 1845, Smith succeeded his late brother [[Hyrum Smith]] as the [[Presiding Patriarch]] of the church,<ref>''[[History of the Church (Joseph Smith)|History of the Church]]'' '''7''':418.</ref> but was [[Disfellowshipped (LDS Church)#Possible outcomes|disfellowshipped]] from the church and removed as both apostle and patriarch in 1845.<ref>[[B. H. Roberts]] (ed.), ''[[History of the Church (Joseph Smith)|History of the Church]]'' '''7''':457\u201359.</ref><ref>Hosea Stout journal, October 6, 1845.</ref> Following 1845, Smith broke with the LDS Church and Brigham Young and held various positions in the [[Strangite]] sect and his own [[Williamite (Mormonism)|Williamite]] sect. Ultimately Smith joined with the [[Reorganized Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints]] (RLDS Church). While Smith believed that he was entitled to become the presiding patriarch or a member of the [[Council of Twelve Apostles (Community of Christ)|Council of Twelve Apostles]] of the RLDS Church, he did not resume his place in the quorum and remained a [[High priest (Latter Day Saints)|high priest]] for the remainder of his life.<ref>Paul M. Edwards, [http://content.lib.utah.edu/u?/dialogue,20600 \"William B. Smith: The Persistent 'Pretender'\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613201355/http://content.lib.utah.edu/u/?%2Fdialogue%2C20600 |date=June 13, 2011 }}, ''[[Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought]]'', vol. '''18''', no. 2 (1985) pp. 128\u201339 at pp. 132\u201339.</ref>\n|-\n| <center>[[File:OrsonPratt.jpg|50px]]</center>\n| [[Orson Pratt]]\n| April 26, 1835\n| Remained with the LDS Church and Brigham Young after 1844 and continued within the Quorum until his death in 1881.\n|-\n| <center>[[File:John F. Boynton.JPG|50px]]</center>\n| [[John F. Boynton]]\n| February 15, 1835\n| Excommunicated from the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints<ref name = \"Naming\"/> in 1838, joined with the short-lived [[Parrishite]]s. After 1844, Boynton left Mormonism and never rejoined any Latter Day Saint sect.\n|-\n| <center>[[File:Lyman E. Johnson.JPG|50px]]</center>\n| [[Lyman E. Johnson]]\n| February 14, 1835\n| Withdrew from the Church of the Latter Day Saints<ref name = \"Naming\"/> in 1837 and was excommunicated in 1838. Johnson died in 1859, having never rejoined any Latter Day Saint sect.\n|-\n| <center>[[File:John E. Page.JPG|50px]]</center>\n| [[John E. Page]]\n| December 19, 1838\n| After 1844, Page joined with the [[Strangite]] and [[Church of Christ (Brewsterite)|Brewsterite]]. Page went on to be an apostle in the [[Church of Christ (Temple Lot)]] or \"Hedrickite\" church.\n|-\n| <center>[[File:John Taylor seated in chair.jpg|50px]]</center>\n| [[John Taylor (Mormon)|John Taylor]]\n| December 19, 1838\n| Remained with the LDS Church and Brigham Young after 1844. In 1880, Taylor became [[List of presidents of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|3rd]] President of the LDS Church.\n|-\n| <center>[[File:Wilford Woodruff 1889.jpg|50px]]</center>\n| [[Wilford Woodruff]]\n| April 26, 1839\n| Remained with the LDS Church and Brigham Young after 1844. In 1889, Woodruff became [[List of presidents of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|4th]] President of the LDS Church.\n|-\n| <center>[[File:GeorgeAlbertSmith.jpg|50px]]</center>\n| [[George A. Smith]]\n| April 26, 1839\n| Remained with the LDS Church and Brigham Young after 1844. In 1868, Smith became [[First Presidency (LDS Church)|First Counselor]] to Young.\n|-\n| <center>[[File:Willardrichards.gif|50px]]</center>\n| [[Willard Richards]]\n| April 14, 1840\n| Remained with the LDS Church and Brigham Young after 1844. In 1847, Richards became [[First Presidency (LDS Church)|Second Counselor]] to Young.\n|-\n| <center>[[File:Lymanwight8.gif|50px]]</center>\n| [[Lyman Wight]]\n| April 8, 1841\n| Wight broke with all sects in 1844. He was ordained [[President of the Church|president]] of his own church, known as the [[Church of Christ (Wightite)|Wightites]].  However, he later sided with the claims of [[William Smith (Latter Day Saints)|William Smith]] and eventually of [[Joseph Smith III]] and the RLDS Church.\n|-\n| <center>[[File:Amasamlyman.png|50px]]</center>\n| [[Amasa M. Lyman]]\n| August 1842\n| Remained with the LDS Church and Brigham Young from 1844 to 1870.  Was stripped of apostleship on October 6, 1867 due to a sermon he preached in [[Dundee]], Scotland, which all but denied the reality of and the necessity for the atonement of Jesus Christ.  In 1869, while not admitting any conversion to the [[Godbeites|Church of Zion]], known as the Godbeites, Lyman began a relationship with [[William S. Godbe]] and the Church of Zion.<ref name=Hefner>{{Citation|last1=Hefner|first1=Loretta L.|title=From Apostle to Apostate: The Personal Struggle of Amasa Mason Lyman|journal=[[Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought|Dialogue]]: A Journal of Mormon Thought|date=1992|volume=16|issue=1|pages=99\u2013101 |url=https://www.dialoguejournal.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/articles/Dialogue_V16N01_92.pdf|accessdate=29 April 2015|publisher=Dialogue Foundation}}</ref>  Lyman associated constantly, preached, and even openly participated in the Church of Zion.<ref name=Hefner/> Due to Lyman's renewed activism and rumors that Lyman would even become [[President of the Church|president]] of the Church of Zion, Lyman was excommunicated from the LDS Church on May 12, 1870.<ref name=Hefner/>\n|}\n\n==The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church)==\n{{Main|Quorum of the Twelve Apostles (LDS Church)}}\n{{For2|the current Quorum of the Twelve Apostles of the LDS Church|[[Quorum of the Twelve Apostles (LDS Church)|Quorum of the Twelve Apostles (current members)]]|a chronology of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles of the LDS Church|[[Chronology of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles (LDS Church)|Quorum of the Twelve Apostles (chronology)]]}}\nIn the LDS Church, the Quorum of the Twelve is officially referred to as the \"Quorum of the Twelve Apostles\" or \"Council of the Twelve Apostles\". The group normally has a leadership role in the church that is second only to the church's [[First Presidency (LDS Church)|First Presidency]]. The Quorum implicitly follows the First Presidency's policies and pronouncements and its members are chosen by the First Presidency. However, when the First Presidency is dissolved\u2014which occurs upon the death of the [[President of the Church (LDS Church)|President of the Church]]\u2014the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles becomes the church's governing body (led by the [[President of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles (LDS Church)|President of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles]]) until they [[ordination|ordain]] a new President of the Church and he chooses counselors, which completes the reorganization of the First Presidency.  Membership in the Quorum of the Twelve is typically a lifetime calling.\n\n[[File:First Presidency and Twelve Apostles 1898.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The [[First Presidency (LDS Church)|First Presidency]] and the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles in September 1898<ref>As seen in this photograph, in September 1898 there were only 11 members of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles (shown here with the three members of the First Presidency).  Church president [[Wilford Woodruff]] had recently died and [[Lorenzo Snow]] left the Quorum to assume the presidency.  [[Rudger Clawson]] would be called the next month, in October 1898, to complete the Quorum.</ref>]]\n\n==Community of Christ==\n{{Main|Council of Twelve Apostles (Community of Christ)}}\n{{For2|the current Council of Twelve Apostles of the Community of Christ|[[Council of Twelve Apostles (Community of Christ)#Current members|Council of Twelve Apostles (current members)]]|a chronology of the Council of Twelve Apostles of the Community of Christ|[[Council of Twelve Apostles (Community of Christ)#1844 to present|Council of Twelve Apostles (chronology)]]}}\nIn the [[Community of Christ]], the Council of Twelve Apostles is one of the governing bodies in the church hierarchy. They hold the priesthood office of [[Twelve Apostles|apostle]] and are responsible for the evangelistic witness of the church. Apostles are also [[High priest (Latter Day Saints)|high priests]] in the [[Priesthood (Community of Christ)|Melchisedec priesthood]] of the church.\n\n==The Church of Jesus Christ (Bickertonite)==\n{{Main|Quorum of Twelve Apostles (Bickertonite)}}\n{{for|a chronology of and current Quorum of the Twelve Apostles of The Church of Jesus Christ|Quorum of Twelve Apostles (Bickertonite)#List of members}}\n[[The Church of Jesus Christ (Bickertonite)]] is the third largest denomination that resulted from the [[Succession crisis (Latter Day Saints)|1844 succession crisis]].\n\nAt a conference in Green Oak, Pennsylvania, in July 1862, leaders of several branches in Pennsylvania, Ohio and Virginia came together and formally organized what they called \"The Church of Jesus Christ\".  [[William Bickerton]] presided over the conference.  Bickerton's two counselors in the newly organized First Presidency were George Barnes and Charles Brown who were ordained apostles. The members of the Quorum of the Twelve at that organization (ordered by seniority) were Arthur Bickerton, Thomas Bickerton, Alexander Bickerton, James Brown, Cummings Cherry, Benjamin Meadowcroft, Joseph Astin, Joseph Knox, William Cadman, James Nichols, John Neish and John Dixon.  At the conference George Barnes reported receiving the \"word of the Lord,\" which he related:\n{{quote|Hear the word of the Lord; Ye are my Sons and Daughters, and I have committed unto you the Keys of the Kingdom, therefore be ye faithful.<ref name=\"Cadman\">{{cite book |last=Cadman |first=W. H. |authorlink=W. H. Cadman |title=A History of the Church of Jesus Christ |year=1945 |publisher=The Church of Jesus Christ|location=Monongahela, PA |language= |isbn= |oclc= |doi= |id= |pages= |chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= }}</ref>}}\n\nIn this church, the \"Quorum of Twelve Apostles\" are the chief governing officers. Currently, the president of the church and his two counselors are not separated from the quorum, as the total number of apostles in the quorum is twelve, as specified in the scriptures. Apostles (and all ministers\u2014commonly called \"elders\") in this church are volunteers and are not given any compensation for their ministry.\n\n==Church of Christ (Temple Lot)==\nIn the [[Church of Christ (Temple Lot)]] the Council of Twelve serves as the head of the church. The church seeks to strictly follow the church organization of the [[Bible]] and the [[Book of Mormon]], and teaches that church offices added by [[Joseph Smith]] after publication of the [[Book of Commandments]], such as a [[President of the Church]] and a [[First Presidency]], were not consistent with the Bible and Book of Mormon, and therefore were not revelations from God {{Harv|Sheldon|1999}}.\n\n==Remnant Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints==\nThe [[Remnant Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints]] has an Apostolic Quorum that is, as yet, incomplete by design. As the Remnant Church seeks to be a \"renewal\" of the Latter Day Saint movement resulting from the 1850s Reorganization, it is attempting to follow similar patterns of that prior reorganization. The [[First Presidency]] of the Remnant Church is not drawn from the apostles. Instead, the president of the church is chosen by [[inheritance|Jewish Laws of Inheritance]].  The current members of the Quorum are: Don Burnett ([[President of the Quorum of the Twelve|President of the Quorum]]), Robert Murie Jr., Terry W. Patience, Roger Tracy, and Mark Deitrick.<ref>https://theremnantchurch.com/index.php/leadership/apostles</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<!--See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes for an explanation of how to generate footnotes using the<ref(erences/)> tags-->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{citation\n | last          = Bergera\n | first         = Gary James\n | contribution  = Church Organization and Government\n | editor1-last  = Reeve\n | editor1-first = W. Paul\n | editor2-last  = Parshall\n | editor2-first = Ardis E.\n | editor2-link  = Ardis E. Parshall\n | title         = [[Mormonism: A Historical Encyclopedia]]\n | location      = Santa Barbara, CA\n | publisher     = [[ABC-CLIO]]\n | year          = 2010\n | isbn          = 9781598841084\n | oclc          = 699490059\n}}.\n*{{citation\n | last          = Flake\n | first         = Lawrence R.\n | chapter       = The Quorum of the Twelve Apostles: An Introduction\n | chapter-url   = http://rsc.byu.edu/archived/prophets-and-apostles-last-dispensation/quorum-twelve-apostles-introduction\n | title         = Prophets and Apostles of the Last Dispensation\n | location      = Provo, UT\n | publisher     = [[Religious Studies Center]], [[Brigham Young University]]\n | year          = 2001\n | isbn          = 1573457973 \n | oclc          = 46943088\n}}\n*{{citation \n | last          = Holzapfel\n | first         = Richard Neitzel\n | contribution  = The Prophet\u2019s Final Charge to the Twelve\n | url 