{"title_page": "Daniel S. Miles", "text_new": "{{Infobox LDS biography\n| name                       = Daniel S. Miles\n| birth_name                 = Daniel Sanborn Miles\n| birth_date                 = {{Birth date|1772|07|23}}\n| birth_place                = [[Sanbornton, New Hampshire|Sanbornton]], [[Province of New Hampshire]]\n| death_date                 = {{death date and age|1845|10|12|1772|07|23}}\n| death_place                = [[Hancock County, Illinois|Hancock County]], [[Illinois]], United States\n| resting_place              = [[Nauvoo Historic District|Old Nauvoo Burial Grounds]]\n| resting_place_coordinates  = {{Coord|40|32|12.12|N|91|21|2.16|W|type:landmark|display=inline|name=Old Nauvoo Burial Grounds}}\n| spouse                     = Electa Chamberlin\n| children                   = \n| parents                    = Josiah Miles<br>Marah Sanborn \n| portals                    = Movement\n| position_or_quorum1        = [[Seventy (Latter Day Saints)#Early Latter Day Saint quorums of seventy|First Seven Presidents of the Seventy]]\n| called_by1                 = [[Joseph Smith, Jr.]]\n| start_date1                = {{start date|1837|4|06}}\n| end_date1                  = {{end date|1845|10|12}}\n}}\n'''Daniel Sanborn Miles''' (July 23, 1772 \u2013 October 12, 1845) was an early [[Mormon]] leader and member of the [[Presidency of the Seventy]] of the [[Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)|Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints]].<!-- Do not change this name to \"The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints\". In the original text of the revelation, as referenced in this article, Smith wrote the name of the church \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints\" --><ref name = 1838name1>''Manuscript History of the Church'', LDS Church Archives, book A-1, p. 37; reproduced in Dean C. Jessee (comp.) (1989). ''The Papers of Joseph Smith: Autobiographical and Historical Writings'' (Salt Lake City, Utah: Deseret Book) '''1''':302\u201303.</ref><ref name = 1838name2>H. Michael Marquardt and [[Wesley P. Walters]] (1994). ''Inventing Mormonism: Tradition and the Historical Record'' (Salt Lake City, Utah: Signature Books) p. 160.</ref>\n\n==Life==\nMiles was born in [[Sanbornton, New Hampshire|Sanbornton]], [[New Hampshire]], and married Electa Chamberlin in [[Ryegate, Vermont|Ryegate]], [[Vermont]], in 1813.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://josephsmithpapers.org/person/daniel-sanborn-miles|title=Daniel Sanborn Miles \u2013 Biography|website=josephsmithpapers.org|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref> [[Orson Pratt]] and [[Lyman E. Johnson]] [[Baptism|baptized]] him in April 1832 in [[Bath, New Hampshire]]. He joined the [[Latter Day Saints]] in [[Kirtland, Ohio|Kirtland]], [[Ohio]] by 1836, and [[Joseph Smith, Jr.]] named him one of the seven Presidents of the Seventy later that year. [[Sidney Rigdon]] and [[Hyrum Smith]] ordained him.<ref name=Grampa>{{cite web |url=http://www.gapages.com/milesds1.htm |title=Daniel S. (Sanborn) Miles |accessdate=2008-04-06 |last= |first= |coauthors= |date= |work= |publisher=Grampa Bill}}</ref>\n\nMiles moved to [[Missouri]] in early 1838, from which he was later expelled with the rest of the Mormons. He was among the first Mormons to settle in [[Nauvoo, Illinois|Nauvoo]], [[Illinois]]. He is mentioned in a [[Doctrine and Covenants]] [[Revelation (Latter Day Saints)|revelation]], D&C 124:138. Miles died in 1845 at the home of [[Josiah Butterfield]] from complications from a fall.<ref name=Grampa/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Wikipedia books\n |1=Seventy (LDS Church)\n}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{LDS70pres|selected=council}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miles, Daniel S.}}\n[[Category:1772 births]]\n[[Category:1845 deaths]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths from falls]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in Illinois]]\n[[Category:American general authorities (LDS Church)]]\n[[Category:Converts to Mormonism]]\n[[Category:People from Sanbornton, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Seventy (LDS Church)]]\n[[Category:Leaders in the Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from Illinois]]\n\n\n{{LDS-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox LDS biography\n| name                       = Daniel S. Miles\n| birth_name                 = Daniel Sanborn Miles\n| birth_date                 = {{Birth date|1772|07|23}}\n| birth_place                = [[Sanbornton, New Hampshire|Sanbornton]], [[Province of New Hampshire]]\n| death_date                 = {{death date and age|1845|10|12|1772|07|23}}\n| death_place                = [[Hancock County, Illinois|Hancock County]], [[Illinois]], United States\n| resting_place              = [[Nauvoo Historic District|Old Nauvoo Burial Grounds]]\n| resting_place_coordinates  = {{Coord|40|32|12.12|N|91|21|2.16|W|type:landmark|display=inline|name=Old Nauvoo Burial Grounds}}\n| spouse                     = Electa Chamberlin\n| children                   = \n| parents                    = Josiah Miles<br>Marah Sanborn \n| portals                    = Movement\n| position_or_quorum1        = [[Seventy (Latter Day Saints)#Early Latter Day Saint quorums of seventy|First Seven Presidents of the Seventy]]\n| called_by1                 = [[Joseph Smith, Jr.]]\n| start_date1                = {{start date|1837|4|06}}\n| end_date1                  = {{end date|1845|10|12}}\n}}\n'''Daniel Sanborn Miles''' (July 23, 1772 \u2013 October 12, 1845) was an early [[Mormon]] leader and member of the [[Presidency of the Seventy]] of the [[Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)|Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints]].<!-- Do not change this name to \"The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints\". In the original text of the revelation, as referenced in this article, Smith wrote the name of the church \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints\" --><ref name = 1838name1>''Manuscript History of the Church'', LDS Church Archives, book A-1, p. 37; reproduced in Dean C. Jessee (comp.) (1989). ''The Papers of Joseph Smith: Autobiographical and Historical Writings'' (Salt Lake City, Utah: Deseret Book) '''1''':302\u201303.</ref><ref name = 1838name2>H. Michael Marquardt and Wesley P. Walters (1994). ''Inventing Mormonism: Tradition and the Historical Record'' (Salt Lake City, Utah: Signature Books) p. 160.</ref>\n\n==Life==\nMiles was born in [[Sanbornton, New Hampshire|Sanbornton]], [[New Hampshire]], and married Electa Chamberlin in [[Ryegate, Vermont|Ryegate]], [[Vermont]], in 1813.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://josephsmithpapers.org/person/daniel-sanborn-miles|title=Daniel Sanborn Miles \u2013 Biography|website=josephsmithpapers.org|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref> [[Orson Pratt]] and [[Lyman E. Johnson]] [[Baptism|baptized]] him in April 1832 in [[Bath, New Hampshire]]. He joined the [[Latter Day Saints]] in [[Kirtland, Ohio|Kirtland]], [[Ohio]] by 1836, and [[Joseph Smith, Jr.]] named him one of the seven Presidents of the Seventy later that year. [[Sidney Rigdon]] and [[Hyrum Smith]] ordained him.<ref name=Grampa>{{cite web |url=http://www.gapages.com/milesds1.htm |title=Daniel S. (Sanborn) Miles |accessdate=2008-04-06 |last= |first= |coauthors= |date= |work= |publisher=Grampa Bill}}</ref>\n\nMiles moved to [[Missouri]] in early 1838, from which he was later expelled with the rest of the Mormons. He was among the first Mormons to settle in [[Nauvoo, Illinois|Nauvoo]], [[Illinois]]. He is mentioned in a [[Doctrine and Covenants]] [[Revelation (Latter Day Saints)|revelation]], D&C 124:138. Miles died in 1845 at the home of [[Josiah Butterfield]] from complications from a fall.<ref name=Grampa/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Wikipedia books\n |1=Seventy (LDS Church)\n}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{LDS70pres|selected=council}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miles, Daniel S.}}\n[[Category:1772 births]]\n[[Category:1845 deaths]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths from falls]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in Illinois]]\n[[Category:American general authorities (LDS Church)]]\n[[Category:Converts to Mormonism]]\n[[Category:People from Sanbornton, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Seventy (LDS Church)]]\n[[Category:Leaders in the Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from Illinois]]\n\n\n{{LDS-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Epachamo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added link toWesley P. Walters", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniel_S._Miles"}
